{{M1 year in topic}}
[[File:Skylintzes+Byzantine Rus conflict.jpg|{{Largethumb}}|right|The [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]] persecute the fleeing [[Kievan Rus'|Rus']].]]
Year '''970''' ('''[[Roman numerals|CMLXX]]''') was a [[common year starting on Saturday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]], the 970th year of the [[Common Era]] (CE) and ''[[Anno Domini]]'' designations, the 970th year of the [[1st millennium]], the 70th year of the [[10th century]], and the 1st year of the [[970s]] decade.

== Events ==
&lt;onlyinclude&gt;

=== By place ===

==== Byzantine Empire ====
* Emperor [[John I Tzimiskes|John I]] delegates the war in the [[Balkans]] to his brother-in-law, the [[Domestic of the Schools]] [[Bardas Skleros]], and to the eunuch general [[Peter (stratopedarches)|Peter Phokas]] who begin to gather a [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] army in [[Thrace (theme)|Thrace]]. At the news of this, a powerful Kievan expeditionary force (30,000 men), along with many [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarians]] and a [[Pechenegs|Pecheneg]] contingent, is sent south over the [[Balkan Mountains]]. After sacking the Bulgarian stronghold of [[Philippopolis (Thracia)|Philippolis]] (modern-day [[Plovdiv]]), they bypass the heavily defended city of [[Edirne|Adrianople]] and turn towards [[Constantinople]].&lt;ref&gt;Brian Todd Carey (2012). ''Road to Manzikert: Byzantine and Islamic Warfare 527–1071'', p. 86. {{ISBN|978-1-84884-215-1}}.&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Battle of Arcadiopolis (970)|Battle of Arcadiopolis]]: John I dispatches an elite force (10–12,000 men) to delay the [[Kievan Rus']]. The Byzantines under Bardas Skleros successfully [[ambush]] the Kievan-Bulgarian invaders at [[Lüleburgaz|Arcadiopolis]] (modern [[Turkey]]). The battle turns into a complete rout, killing thousands. Grand Prince [[Sviatoslav I of Kiev|Sviatoslav I]] is driven out of Thrace and withdraws his forces to the fortress city of [[Silistra]].&lt;ref&gt;Brian Todd Carey (2012). ''Road to Manzikert: Byzantine and Islamic Warfare 527–1071'', pp.86–87. {{ISBN|978-1-84884-215-1}}.&lt;/ref&gt;
* Summer &amp;ndash; [[Bardas Phokas the Younger|Bardas Phokas]] ('''the Younger''') and his family rebel against their own cousin, John I. Bardas is proclaimed 'emperor' by his troops at [[Kayseri|Caesarea]], but the rebellion is extinguished by Bardas Skleros. Phokas and his relatives are captured and [[exile]]d to the island of [[Chios]] ([[Aegean Sea]]).

==== Europe ====
* Summer &amp;ndash; Byzantine-Imperial truce: Emperor [[Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto I]] ('''the Great''') meets with John I at [[Bari]] and accepts a permanent peace agreement. [[Pandulf Ironhead|Pandulf I]] ('''Ironhead''') is released from captivity in [[Constantinople]] (see [[969]]).
* The oldest preserved document (by Otto I) mentions [[Leibnitz]] in [[Styria]] (modern [[Austria]]).
* [[Eric the Victorious]] becomes the first (documented) king of [[Sweden]] in [[Uppland]].
* [[Skagul Toste]] leads a [[Vikings|Viking]] expedition to [[Kingdom of England|England]] and demands [[Danegeld]].

==== Africa ====
* [[Al-Hasan ibn Ubayd Allah ibn Tughj|Al-Hasan ibn Ubayd Allah]], Ikhshidid governor of [[Jund Filastin|Palestine]], is defeated and taken prisoner by General [[Ja'far ibn Fallah]] in [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]]. Ending the [[Ikhshidid dynasty|Ikhshidid Dynasty]] as a ruling power. 
* Construction is completed on [[Al-Azhar Mosque]] in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] (the world's oldest [[Islam]]ic university).

==== Asia ====
* A major [[volcano]] erupts in [[Lake Mashū]], [[Japan]] (approximate date).
&lt;/onlyinclude&gt;

